!!【柯林斯英汉双解大词典】

:<div>

cheat /tʃiːt/

(cheating,cheated,cheats) 

1. V-I When someone cheats , they do not obey a set of rules which they should be obeying, for example in a game or exam. 舞弊; 作弊 

例： Students may be tempted to cheat in order to get into top schools. 学生们可能禁不住会作弊，以便能进一流学校。 

2. cheating N-UNCOUNT 舞弊; 作弊 

例： In an election in 1988, he was accused of cheating by his opponent. 在1988年的一次竞选中，他被对手指控舞弊。 

3. V-T If someone cheats you out of something, they get it from you by behaving dishonestly. 诈取 

例： The company engaged in a deliberate effort to cheat them out of their pensions. 该公司曾蓄意诈取他们的养老金。 

4. N-COUNT Someone who is a cheat does not obey a set of rules which they should be obeying. 舞弊者 

例： Cheats will be disqualified. 舞弊者将被取消资格。

